description:
This crash occurred on a two lane undivided roadway at an intersection with a 2 lane
                        undivided side road. The posted speed limit on the two lane roadway on which the crash occurred
                        was 89KMPH (55MPH). The posted speed limit on the side road was 48KMPH (30MPH) and the side road
                        had a stop sign. It was dark at the time of the crash and the roadway was unlighted. The roadway
                        was dry and it was cloudy. This crash occurred on a weekday evening.


                        Vehicle #1, a 1996 Plymouth Voyager minivan, was attempting to make a westbound left turn, from
                        the side road, onto the two lane undivided roadway. The driver stated he got halfway out and
                        stopped, assuming the other vehicle would go around him. Vehicle #2, a 2005 Nissan Altima
                        heading east impacted with the drivers side of Vehicle #1, with its front.


                        The Plymouth Voyager was driven by a belted 89 year old male who was transported to an area
                        hospital, treated and released. The driver stated he thought the other vehicle was far enough
                        away. It should be noted here that the driver takes prescription medications for high blood
                        pressure and two pain killing medications, for a back injury, which state drowsiness as a
                        possible side effect.


                        The Critical Precrash Event coded to this vehicle was: This Vehicle Traveling Turning Left at
                        Intersection. The Critical Reason for the Critical Precrash Event was coded as Driver Related
                        Factor Decision Error, False Assumptioin of Other's Actions.


                        The Nissan Altima was driven by a belted 30 year old female and there were two passengers in
                        this vehicle, a belted 34 year old male and an young child in a child restraint. All three
                        passengers in this vehicle were transported to an area hospital, although the child was not
                        injured. The driver and other passenger were treated and released. This driver did not answer
                        requests for interviews.


                        The Critical Precrash Event coded to this vehicle was: Other vehicle encroachment from crossing
                        street, turning into opposite direction. No Critical Reason for the Critical Precrash Event was
                        coded to this vehicle.


                        Police did not consider alcohol or illegal drugs to be a factor and ordered no tests for either
                        driver
